  "title": "",
  "body": " I'm thinking of a polyhedron containing 12 faces. Seven are triangles and four are quadralaterals. The polyhedron has 11 vertices including those around the mystery face. How many sides does the last face have?   Say the last polyhedron has edges, and also vertices. The total number of edges the polyhedron has then is . In particular, we know the last face must have an odd number of edges. We also have that . By Euler's formula, we have , and solving for we get , so the last face is a pentagon.  "
